  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Writer-based prose is text organized around the writer\u0026rsquo;s own process of discovery — following the path the writer took to understand the material. Reader-based prose is text reorganized for the reader\u0026rsquo;s needs — structured by what the reader needs to know, in the order they need it.\nLinda Flower introduced this distinction as part of the cognitive process model of writing she developed with John Hayes. Writer-based prose is a natural product of thinking-through-writing: the writer explores the topic, makes connections, and follows associations. The result often reads like a narrative of discovery — \u0026ldquo;first I noticed X, then I realized Y, which led me to Z\u0026rdquo; — rather than a direct statement of the conclusion [@flowerhayes1981].\n",
